Hi! Great question. When you convert a string to a double using `std::stod`, if the number represented by the string is out of the range representable by a `double`, `std::stod` will throw an exception of type `std::out_of_range`.

So, to check whether the number in the string is out of the bounds of a double, you can try to convert it inside a try-catch block and catch the `std::out_of_range` exception.

Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <limits>

int main() {
    std::string s = "1e400"; // example number larger than double max

    try {
        double d = std::stod(s);
        std::cout << "Converted value: " << d << std::endl;

        // Optionally, you can check if the value is finite
        if (d == std::numeric_limits<double>::infinity() || d == -std::numeric_limits<double>::infinity()) {
            std::cout << "Value is out of double range (infinity)." << std::endl;
        } else {
            std::cout << "Value is within double range." << std::endl;
        }
    } catch (const std::out_of_range& e) {
        std::cout << "Out of range error: " << e.what() << std::endl;
    } catch (const std::invalid_argument& e) {
        std::cout << "Invalid argument: " << e.what() << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Explanation:
- `std::stod` throws `std::out_of_range` if the converted value is out of the range of representable values by a double.
- It throws `std::invalid_argument` if the string does not contain a valid number.
- You can also check if the converted value is infinity, which means it overflowed.

This way, you can detect if the string represents a number out of the double range.

