To add syntax highlighting so that every word or sentence highlighted by quotation marks (single or double quotes) is colored red in the rendered MarkdownBlock, we need to customize the renderer to wrap quoted text in a span with a red color style.

Since the MarkdownBlock uses `marked` to parse the markdown and uses a renderer to generate HTML, the best place to implement this is in the renderer's `text` method, which is called for plain text nodes.

We will override the `text` renderer method to find quoted text and wrap it in `<span style="color: red;">...</span>`.

Here is the modified part of the `MarkdownBlock.renderer` with the added `text` method:

```js
static renderer = Object.assign({
	heading (text, level, _raw, slugger) {
		level = Math.min(6, level + (this.hmin - 1));
		const id = slugger.slug(text);
		const hlinks = this.hlinks;

		let content;

		if (hlinks === null) {
			// No heading links
			content = text;
		}
		else {
			content = `<a href="#${id}" class="anchor">`;

			if (hlinks === "") {
				// Heading content is the link
				content += text + "</a>";
			}
			else {
				// Headings are prepended with a linked symbol
				content += hlinks + "</a>" + text;
			}
		}

		return `<h${level} id="${id}">${content}</h${level}>`;
	},

	code (code, language, escaped) {
		if (this._contentFromHTML) {
			// Inline HTML code needs to be escaped to not be parsed as HTML by the browser
			// This results in marked double-escaping it, so we need to unescape it
			code = code.replace(/&amp;(?=[lg]t;)/g, "&");
		}
		else {
			// Remote code may include characters that need to be escaped to be visible in HTML
			code = code.replace(/</g, "&lt;");
		}

		return `<pre class="language-${language}"><code>${code}</code></pre>`;
	},

	text(text) {
		// Replace quoted text with span styled red
		// Match text inside single or double quotes, including multiple quoted parts
		// We will replace each quoted part with a span

		// Use a regex to find quoted parts
		// This regex matches quotes and the content inside, including escaped quotes inside
		// For simplicity, we assume no escaped quotes inside

		return text.replace(/(["'])(.+?)\1/g, (match, quote, content) => {
			return `<span style="color: red;">${quote}${content}${quote}</span>`;
		});
	}
}, MarkdownSpan.renderer);
```

### Explanation:
- Added a `text` method to the renderer.
- It uses a regex `/(["'])(.+?)\1/g` to find quoted text (either single or double quotes).
- Each match is wrapped in a `<span style="color: red;">...</span>` to color it red.
- The rest of the renderer remains unchanged.

