To use different Spring Security filters based on the `Referer` header value, you can create a custom filter that inspects the `Referer` header and then delegates to different filter logic accordingly. Since Spring Security filter chains are typically configured globally or per request matcher, but not directly per header, you need to implement this logic inside a filter.

Here’s a step-by-step approach:

### 1. Create Custom Filters for Each Referer

Create separate filters for each type of `Referer` you want to handle differently. For example:

```java
public class RefererFilterA extends OncePerRequestFilter {
    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, FilterChain filterChain)
            throws ServletException, IOException {
        // Your logic for Referer A
        System.out.println("RefererFilterA applied");
        filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}

public class RefererFilterB extends OncePerRequestFilter {
    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, FilterChain filterChain)
            throws ServletException, IOException {
        // Your logic for Referer B
        System.out.println("RefererFilterB applied");
        filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}
```

### 2. Create a Delegating Filter That Chooses Which Filter to Apply

Create a filter that reads the `Referer` header and delegates to the appropriate filter:

```java
public class RefererDelegatingFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {

    private final RefererFilterA filterA;
    private final RefererFilterB filterB;

    public RefererDelegatingFilter(RefererFilterA filterA, RefererFilterB filterB) {
        this.filterA = filterA;
        this.filterB = filterB;
    }

    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response, FilterChain filterChain)
            throws ServletException, IOException {
        String referer = request.getHeader("Referer");

        if (referer != null) {
            if (referer.contains("exampleA.com")) {
                filterA.doFilter(request, response, filterChain);
                return;
            } else if (referer.contains("exampleB.com")) {
                filterB.doFilter(request, response, filterChain);
                return;
            }
        }

        // Default behavior if no referer or no match
        filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}
```

### 3. Register the Delegating Filter in Your Security Configuration

In your Spring Security configuration, register the `RefererDelegatingFilter` at the appropriate place in the filter chain:

```java
@Configuration
@EnableWebSecurity
public class SecurityConfig extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {

    @Bean
    public RefererFilterA refererFilterA() {
        return new RefererFilterA();
    }

    @Bean
    public RefererFilterB refererFilterB() {
        return new RefererFilterB();
    }

    @Bean
    public RefererDelegatingFilter refererDelegatingFilter() {
        return new RefererDelegatingFilter(refererFilterA(), refererFilterB());
    }

    @Override
    protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
            // other security config
            .addFilterBefore(refererDelegatingFilter(), UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class);
    }
}
```

### Notes

- Adjust the position of the filter in the chain (`addFilterBefore` or `addFilterAfter`) depending on your needs.
- You can extend this pattern to support more referer values and filters.
- Make sure your filters call `filterChain.doFilter()` to continue the chain unless you want to block the request.

---

If you want to apply completely different security configurations based on the referer, that is more complex because Spring Security matches requests based on URL patterns, not headers. The above approach is the most straightforward way to apply different filter logic based on the `Referer` header.

In C++, automatic garbage collection is not built into the language like in some other languages (e.g., Java, Python). However, you can achieve automatic memory management for linked lists by using smart pointers, such as `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr`, which automatically delete the objects they own when they go out of scope.

Here is an example of a singly linked list implemented with `std::unique_ptr` to automatically manage memory:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>

template <typename T>
class LinkedList {
private:
    struct Node {
        T data;
        std::unique_ptr<Node> next;

        Node(T val) : data(val), next(nullptr) {}
    };

    std::unique_ptr<Node> head;

public:
    LinkedList() : head(nullptr) {}

    // Add a new node at the front
    void push_front(T val) {
        auto new_node = std::make_unique<Node>(val);
        new_node->next = std::move(head);
        head = std::move(new_node);
    }

    // Print the list
    void print() const {
        Node* current = head.get();
        while (current) {
            std::cout << current->data << " -> ";
            current = current->next.get();
        }
        std::cout << "nullptr\n";
    }

    // Destructor is not needed explicitly because unique_ptr will clean up
};

int main() {
    LinkedList<int> list;
    list.push_front(3);
    list.push_front(2);
    list.push_front(1);

    list.print();  // Output: 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> nullptr

    // No need to manually delete nodes; unique_ptr handles it automatically
    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation:
- Each `Node` owns its `next` node via a `std::unique_ptr`.
- When a `Node` is destroyed, its `next` node is automatically destroyed recursively.
- The `LinkedList` owns the head node via a `std::unique_ptr`.
- No manual `delete` calls are needed; memory is automatically freed when the list or nodes go out of scope.

If you want a doubly linked list or shared ownership, you can use `std::shared_ptr` and `std::weak_ptr`, but for most singly linked lists, `std::unique_ptr` is sufficient and more efficient.

